Analyzing Global Health: Causes of Death Across Countries¶

By: Muzzamal Saleem

Introduction¶

In this tutorial, I will explore into the historical data on causes of death worldwide, shedding light on global health trends and the impact of different diseases over time. By exploring this data, we aim to understand better how diseases affect populations and how effective our health interventions have been. This isn't just about numbers—it's about saving lives by identifying what has worked and what hasn't in public health. For data scientists, this presents a unique opportunity to apply analytical skills to solve real-world problems that can make a difference, making this project both crucial and compelling.

Data Collection¶

In this section, we'll cover the initial step of the data science lifecycle: Data Collection. Data collection is a critical phase where data scientists gather information from various sources to address specific questions or hypotheses. In our case, we're using a dataset from Kaggle, a platform that hosts datasets for data science and machine learning projects.

Dataset Overview¶

You can download the dataset at Kaggle - Cause of Deaths Around the World. Our dataset, titled "cause_of_deaths.csv", contains information on the causes of death across different countries and years. Each row in the dataset represents a country in a specific year, with columns detailing deaths due to various causes.

Loading the Dataset¶

To begin working with this dataset, we first need to load it into our Python environment using the Pandas library, a powerful tool for data manipulation and analysis. If you haven't already installed Pandas, you can do so by running pip install pandas in your notebook or command line. For a great introduction to using Pandas, check out the official 10-minute guide to Pandas. It's a quick and informative read that will get you up to speed on the basics of this powerful tool!

Below is the Python code to load our dataset (make sure the dataset is in your working directory):

In this stage, we delve into the dataset through visualizations and statistical analysis to discover patterns, identify anomalies, and test hypotheses.

Introduction¶

This visualization aims to highlight the top 10 causes of death globally, providing a clear and impactful view of major health challenges faced worldwide. By identifying and visualizing these leading causes, we can better understand public health priorities and the importance of medical research and healthcare interventions.

Let's dive a bit deeper and look at how the impact of each disease has changed over the years. We're not just looking at raw numbers; instead, we'll calculate the percentage change year over year to see trends in how each disease's death toll has risen or fallen.

We have to make sure to extract the correct columns for diseases, starting from the fourth column since the first three are Country, Code, and Year.

In [ ]:
disease_columns = data.columns[3:]  # Skipping Country, Code, Year

Group the data by year and sum up the deaths for each cause to see the total impact per year.

In [ ]:
annual_deaths = data.groupby('Year').sum()[disease_columns]

To spot trends, I calculate the year-over-year percentage change for each disease. This gives us a sense of whether things are getting better or worse.

In [ ]:
annual_death_pct_change = annual_deaths.pct_change().dropna() * 100  # Dropping the first year as it'll be NaN

Now, for the fun part—visualizing these changes! I'll create a separate plot for each disease to clearly see their trends.

It seems we have a fascinating set of trends and patterns across various diseases over the years.

  • Trend Shifts: Diseases like HIV/AIDS are showing a remarkable decline, suggesting the success of ongoing global health efforts.

  • Seasonal Patterns: 'Diarrheal Diseases' often peak annually, hinting at influences from seasonal changes like rainfall and temperature, which affect how these diseases spread.

  • Notable Outliers: Spikes in the 'Exposure to Forces of Nature' graph may point to major natural disasters, highlighting their dramatic impact on mortality rates. Similarly, sharp increases in 'Conflict and Terrorism' suggest the severe effects of conflicts and attacks on human lives.

Now let's dive deeper. In this section, we'll test hypotheses and apply machine learning to uncover further insights from our data. Ready to explore what the numbers reveal about global health trends? Let’s get started!

Model: Analysis, hypothesis testing, & ML¶

Using Linear Regression to Predict Trends in Disease Mortality¶

Given our exploratory analysis on the trends and patterns in mortality rates across various diseases, we now turn to a predictive model. Linear regression stands out as a powerful tool for understanding and forecasting future trends based on historical data. To get a clearer picture of how linear regression works and why it's so effective, check out this helpful video on YouTube. It breaks down the concept in an easy-to-grasp manner, perfect for anyone looking to deepen their understanding.

Example Hypothesis for Tuberculosis:¶

Hypothesis: Over the years, public health initiatives and improvements in medical treatments have led to a decrease in mortality rates for Tuberculosis. We expect to see a negative slope in a linear regression model that predicts mortality rate based on the year, confirming this decreasing trend.

Null Hypothesis: There is no significant trend (decrease) in the Tuberculosis mortality rates over the years.

To test this hypothesis, we will use linear regression analysis on Tuberculosis mortality data.

First things first, we need to load our dataset and prepare it for analysis. We'll sum up the deaths for each cause by year, which helps us focus on trends over time. Let's focus on Tuberculosis and extract the data related to Tuberculosis deaths from our annual summaries.

In [ ]:
# Load the dataset
data = pd.read_csv('cause_of_deaths.csv')

# Sum deaths for each cause by year
annual_deaths = data.groupby('Year').sum()

# Select Tuberculosis for analysis
tb_deaths = annual_deaths['Tuberculosis']

Now, let's see if there's a trend in the Tuberculosis mortality rates over the years using linear regression. Before we do that, we transform our years and death counts into the right shape for analysis. This step gets our data ready for the model.

In [ ]:
import numpy as np
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression

# Prepare the data for modeling
years = np.array(tb_deaths.index).reshape(-1, 1)
deaths = np.array(tb_deaths.values).reshape(-1, 1)

# Create and fit the model
model = LinearRegression()
model.fit(years, deaths)

With our model fitted, we can predict the mortality rates for the given years and plot these predictions against the actual data to see the trend.

In [ ]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Predict deaths for the given years
predicted_deaths = model.predict(years)

# Plotting the actual vs predicted deaths
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.scatter(years, deaths, color='blue', label='Actual Deaths')
plt.plot(years, predicted_deaths, color='red', label='Predicted Deaths by Model')
plt.title('Tuberculosis Deaths Over Years')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Number of Deaths')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Take a look at this graph! It shows both the actual and predicted Tuberculosis deaths over the years. Our linear regression model is performing impressively, closely matching the actual data. The trend line clearly illustrates a steady decline in deaths, indicating that efforts to combat Tuberculosis have been effective. It's encouraging to see how well the model captures this downward trend, giving us a solid basis for predicting future trends.

Finally, let's statistically test if there's a significant trend in the data. We'll use a t-test on the slope of the regression line.

In [ ]:
from scipy import stats

# Null Hypothesis: No decrease in tuberculosis deaths over the years
slope, intercept, r_value, p_value, std_err = stats.linregress(years.flatten(), deaths.flatten())

print("p-value for hypothesis test:", p_value)

# Determine the outcome of the hypothesis test
if p_value < 0.05:
    print("Reject the null hypothesis - There is a significant decrease in deaths.")
else:
    print("Fail to reject the null hypothesis - No significant change in deaths.")

p-value for hypothesis test: 3.6757836832769754e-22
Reject the null hypothesis - There is a significant decrease in deaths.

Wow, that's a striking result! With a p-value of approximately 3.68e-22, it's extremely low—way below the common threshold of 0.05 used to judge statistical significance. This means we can confidently reject the null hypothesis, which stated that there's no decrease in tuberculosis deaths over the years.

What does this tell us? Well, it's clear evidence that there has been a significant decrease in tuberculosis mortality rates over the years covered by our dataset. This could be attributed to improvements in healthcare, better access to medical treatment, effective public health campaigns, or advancements in medication. It's a positive sign that efforts to combat tuberculosis are paying off!

Exploring a New Example: Clustering Countries Based on Cardiovascular Disease Deaths¶

After diving into linear regression, let's try a different approach to understand global health data. This time, we’ll use a clustering algorithm to group countries based on the total deaths from cardiovascular diseases over all the years. Clustering can help us identify patterns that aren't immediately obvious and understand which countries share similar health challenges.

First up, we load our dataset and prepare it by summing up the cardiovascular disease deaths for each country.

In [ ]:
import pandas as pd

# Load the dataset
data = pd.read_csv('cause_of_deaths.csv')

# Aggregate 'Cardiovascular Diseases' for each country over all the years
cardiovascular_sum = data.groupby('Country/Territory')['Cardiovascular Diseases'].sum()

After aggregation, we'll convert the series to a DataFrame for easier handling and normalize the data to prepare for clustering.

In [ ]:
# Convert to DataFrame for easier handling
cardiovascular_sum_df = cardiovascular_sum.reset_index()

# Normalize the data
X = cardiovascular_sum_df[['Cardiovascular Diseases']].values
X_normalized = np.log1p(X)  # Using log1p for normalization to handle large values

Now, let’s apply K-Means clustering to group the data into 15 clusters. If you're curious to learn more about how K-Means clustering works, this video provides a clear and detailed explanation. It's a great resource for visually seeing how data points are grouped into clusters, which can enhance your understanding of the process. Highly recommended for a deeper dive into the topic!

In [ ]:
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans

# Initialize KMeans with 15 clusters
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=15, random_state=42)
kmeans.fit(X_normalized)

# Assign clusters back to the original data
cardiovascular_sum_df['Cluster'] = kmeans.labels_

clusters_countries = []

    cluster_data = cardiovascular_sum_df[cardiovascular_sum_df['Cluster'] == cluster_number]
    countries_in_cluster = cluster_data[['Country/Territory', 'Cardiovascular Diseases']].values
    clusters_countries.append((cluster_number, countries_in_cluster))

Now that we've identified our clusters, let’s take a closer look at what these groupings tell us. Each cluster tells a story about the countries within it, from those struggling with high death rates to those managing to keep these numbers relatively low. Here are some key observations:

  • Large Clusters: Clusters like Cluster 9, which includes populous countries like China, India, Russia, and the United States, show extremely high numbers of deaths, reflecting both the population size and the high prevalence of cardiovascular diseases in these countries.
  • Smaller Clusters: On the other end of the spectrum, we have clusters like Cluster 11 with very small island nations like Niue and Tokelau, showcasing minimal cardiovascular deaths, which could be attributed to their smaller populations.
  • Intermediate Clusters: Clusters like Cluster 8 include countries with moderate cardiovascular death counts, such as Bangladesh, Egypt, and France. This suggests a mixed influence of healthcare systems' effectiveness and underlying population health dynamics.

Interpretation: Insight & Policy Decision¶

As we wrap up our analysis of global health data, here are some clear insights and how they could guide public health policy:

Insights:¶

  • Trend Analysis with Linear Regression: The significant decrease in tuberculosis deaths showcases the effectiveness of health campaigns and treatments. Continued support and funding in these areas can further reduce mortality rates.

  • Outlier Identification in Data Trends: Spikes in deaths from natural disasters and conflicts highlight the need for robust emergency planning and infrastructure.

  • Mortality Distribution Analysis: A deep dive into mortality causes points to cardiovascular diseases and neoplasms as top priorities for healthcare strategies.

  • Clustering for Cardiovascular Disease Deaths: Identifying clusters of countries with high cardiovascular deaths allows for targeted cardiovascular health interventions, tailored to each cluster's specific needs and conditions.

Policy Recommendations:¶

  • Strengthen Healthcare Systems: Strengthening the healthcare system with better facilities and more healthcare professionals is crucial.

  • Educational Programs: Implement educational programs that promote preventive measures and healthy lifestyle choices, especially in countries with high rates of lifestyle-related diseases.

  • Monitor and Evaluate: Keep a close eye on health policies to ensure they're effective and tweak them as needed.

  • Research and Development: Invest in research to delve deeper into the causes of diseases with less significant declines in mortality rates, fostering innovation in medical treatments and public health interventions.

Conclusion¶

This project showcases how data science can transform public health strategies. With continued data-driven approaches, we can fight diseases more effectively and lift global health standards. Thanks for joining me on this insightful journey!
